    "attributes": {
        "action": "Make Sexual Education Mandatory For Academic Years 3 and Up",
        "additional_details": "A government literary review, published in 2021, concluded that pornography viewing was a factor in poor attitudes against women and girls, including 1. Viewing women as sex objects; 2. Shaping men\u2019s sexual expectations of women; 3. Acceptance of sexual aggression towards women; and 4. Perpetration of sexual aggression. Yet, the governments recent policy paper, aiming to \"halve violence against women and girls in a decade\" has no plea for mandatory sexual education within all primary schools.",
        "background": "The Children\u2019s Commissioner found that 10% of children are exposed to pornography by age 9 (academic years 4 and 5) - that jumps to 27% by age 11(academic years 6 and 7). Yet, despite studies linking porn to aggressive sexual behaviour, sexual education is still not mandatory in all primary schools.",
